uestions about how public art is created and for whom it is intended. In The New Public Art, Mara Polgovsky Ezcurra, together with a number of scholars, artists, and activists, looks at the rise of community-focused art projects, from collective cinema to off-stage dance and theatre, and the creation of anti-monuments that have redefined what public art is and how people have engaged with it across the country since the 1980s. The New Public Art investigates the reemergence of collective practices in response to privatization, individualism, and alienating violence. Focusing on the intersection of art, politics, and notions of public participation and belonging, contributors argue that a new, non-state-led understanding of "the public" came into being in Mexico between the mid-1980s and the late 2010s. During this period, community-based public art bore witness to the human costs of abuses of state and economic power while proposing alternative forms of artistic creation, activism, and cultural organization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and social actionzMexico. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszMexico. 0aArtists and communityzMexico. 0aArtistsxPolitical activityzMexico. 0aCommunity arts projectszMexico. 0aGroup work in artzMexico. 0aPublic artzMexico. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aMexico City, Ciudad de México, CDMX, Diego Rivera, José Clemente Orozco, Rufino Tamayo, agora, political art, state-sponsored art, visual culture, art history, performance studies, dance, theatre, teatro, cinema, bailar, Mexican art, Community.1 aAbel, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrillo, Gabriela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordero Reiman, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores Magón, Diego